    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-12-21T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-12-21T12:00:00-05:00" n="465"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d465">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.2531/606: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Chile</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bowers</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Santiago</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-12-21T13:00:00-04:00"
                            >December 21, 1939—l p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 12:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>239. Referring to my telegram No. 238 of December 20, 7 p.m.,<note n="41"
                        xml:id="d465fn41">Not printed.</note> conveying Chile’s consent to the
                    publication of a statement at Washington to the effect that the pending trade
                    agreement will not affect the copper tax in the United States,<note n="42"
                        xml:id="d465fn42">For statement to the press December 21, see Department of
                        State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, December 23, 1939, p. 733.</note> it
                    is important to explain that Chile’s consent was based upon the telephone
                    communication received by the Embassy from the Department on the afternoon of
                    December 18 to the effect that Chile’s acceptance would result in very
                    sympathetic consideration by the Department to a revision of Schedules I and II
                    to render them more favorable to Chile.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bowers</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
